When using the IServiceProvider I have a number of services that implement IHostedService that are long living and directly callable. The issue is that the service is not fully accessible until after it has been started and initialized. In this scenario there are a number of issues.

doing the following:
```
services.AddHostedService<ServiceA>();
services.AddSingleton<IServiceA,ServiceA>();
services.AddSingleton<IServiceB,ServiceA>();
```
results in 3 instances of ServiceA.

doing the following
```
public static IServiceCollection AddServiceA(this IServiceCollection services)
{
    var slimLock = new ReaderWriterLockSlim();
    ServiceA instance = default;
    ServiceA getInstance(IServiceProvider sp)
    {
        return slimLock.Execute(() => instance == default, () => instance = new ServiceA(sp),
            () => instance);
    }
    services.AddHostedService(getInstance);
    services.AddSingleton<IServiceA>(getInstance);
    services.AddSingleton<IServiceB>(getInstance);
    return services;
}
```
ensures a single instance but leaves the slimLock and instance variable lingering. It also requires an extension to add an IHostedService using and instance (see below)

```
public static IServiceCollection AddHostedService<THostedService>(this IServiceCollection services, Func<IServiceProvider, THostedService> implementationFactory) 
            where THostedService : class, IHostedService
{
    services.TryAddEnumerable(ServiceDescriptor.Singleton<IHostedService, THostedService>(implementationFactory));
    return services;
}
```

All of this is a little messy but gets me to my point. For purposes where services have complex startup logic a IHostedService provides a convenient way to defer it asynchronously but a number of things are required to make the service startup awaitable as described here:

```
public interface IServiceA { }
public interface IServiceB { }
public class ServiceA : IHostedService, IServiceB, IServiceA, IAsyncService
{
    private bool _started = false;
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _startedEvent = new ManualResetEventSlim(false);

    public ServiceA(IServiceProvider sp) { }


    public async Task<bool> StatupCompletedAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = default)
    {
        await _startedEvent.WaitHandle.AsTask(timeout ?? Timeout.InfiniteTimeSpan);
        return _started;
    }

    public Task StopAsync(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        //...
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    public Task StartAsync(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        /*
         * Do some async initialization
         */
        _startedEvent.Set();
        //...
        return Task.FromResult(true);
    }
}
```

From here a couple of extension methods are needed in order to make the startup awaitable.
```
namespace Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection
{
    using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
    public static class ServiceProviderAsyncServiceExtensions
    {
        public static async Task<T> GetServiceAsync<T>(this IServiceProvider provider) where T : IAsyncService
        {
            var result = Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection.ServiceProviderServiceExtensions.GetService<T>(provider);
            if (result != default)
            {
                await result.StatupCompletedAsync();
            }
            return result;
        }

        public static async Task<T> GetRequiredServiceAsync<T>(this IServiceProvider provider) where T : IAsyncService
        {
            var result = ServiceProviderServiceExtensions.GetRequiredService<T>(provider);
            if (result != default)
            {
                await result.StatupCompletedAsync();
            }
            return result;
        }
    }
}
```

and then a caller can invoke
```
var service = await ServiceProvider.GetRequiredServiceAsync<IServiceA>();
```

The last piece of the puzzle is a means to coordinate access to ```_startedEvent``` to prevent circular refences which can be achieved using an singleton ```ReaderWriterLockSlim``` somewhere in the ServiceProvider instance.

This is fairly simple to implement and can enrich dependency injection further
